<span class="s1">&lt;/dl&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Pygame 1.9 comes with support for interfacing cameras, allowing you to capture</span>
<span class="s0">still images, watch live streams, and do some simple computer vision.  This</span>
<span class="s0">tutorial will cover all of those use cases, providing code samples you can base</span>
<span class="s0">your app or game on. <span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Since get_image() is a blocking call that could take quite a bit of time on a</span>
<span class="s0">slow camera, this example uses query_image() to see if the camera is ready.</span>
<span class="s0">This allows you to separate the framerate of your game from that of your camera.</span>
<span class="s0">It is also possible to have the camera capturing images in a separate thread,</span>
<span class="s0">for approximately the same performance gain, if you find that your camera does</span>
<span class="s0">not support the query_image() function correctly.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>

<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">By using the camera, transform, and mask modules, pygame can do some basic</span>
